It's in Canadian interests to make reasonable efforts to ensure that any negotiations over NAFTA begin with a focus on developing changes that benefit all three member States and on avoiding partisan political scapegoating pandering to domestic audiences by the negotiators.

Care must be taken, however, to ensure that Canadian efforts in this regard do not suggest that Canada, faced with bullying tactics, is prepared to settle for disadvantageous terms or to side inappropriately with the US at Mexico's expense.

Hard bargaining by each of the three NAFTA member States is to be expected and Canada must be prepared to give way on some issues if this can lead to changes that, on balance, improve North American trading conditions.  However, Canada must strongly resist pressure to make unilateral concessions or to become the junior partner in efforts to gang up with the US against third nations. Such craven responses can only harm Canada in the long run.

Equity does not come from giving everybody the exact same education regardless of the needs of the student.  Some people need accommodations because they have dyslexia or some other learning disability.  Some need braille because they are blind.  Some are very bright and tune out in a regular classroom because they learnt the material years before.   Some  need small classrooms because they suffer from anxiety or autism.  One solution does not work for all students.  We need to have high standards for all students, but we need a variety of  classroom environments to get to graduation.  

Let's make specialized classrooms available to all parts of the city because everybody wants to see their children achieve a better life.   It is worth the money because students need to be engaged in their studies.  Let's not destroy what works in order to pretend that this will improve equity. Working in the bowels of government, I'd be concerned about living with proportional representation. I like the idea philosophically, but in practice I believe it would mean indecision, inaction and weak government. Having a majority means that you can move forward with a strategy and if you misstep too many times, well...it generally ends fairly quickly. The Alberta NDP have a chance to make things happen with a 4-year term that would have been a minority government with anything but first-past-the-post. I'm not living in Alberta and I might be wrong, but I suspect there wasn't a cry for proportional representation in the aftermath of their last election. The theory is that people would be more proportionally represented, but in the way that minority governments are impotent and unable to cultivate a meaningful platform, I would expect anything but proportional constituent representation. Would government become more collaborative...are we missing the point of competitive democracy?

Alaska residents collectively own the minerals in Alaska. This is what effectively is happening: 

The mineral extraction companies, primarily oil, pay the collective for the oil. Right off the top, the state taxes those earnings 50%, the remaining earnings go into an interest bearing account collectively owned by the Residents. The residents get a dividend from a 5 year average of the interests. Now the state taxes you again, ~50% of those earnings 1250$. 

Imagine this, you own a factory, you rent the factory out to a company making widgets, for rent you get a cut of the profits of the widget. State taxes you 50% of that profit. You wisely invest the remaining 50% and cash out on the interest from that investment. Now the state taxes you another 50% when you collect that interest. The state is taxing you 50% of everything related to your widget earnings. Meanwhile the state gives your renter a cut of your earnings, "tax credit". 

Redistribution of your wealth to gov and company!

The paper I wrote for the 2011 annual CEA meeting proposes a better way of calculating the owner-occupied housing component of the CPI.
http://economics.ca/2011/papers/BA0017-1.pdf
The accounting approach to measuring  OOH used in the Canadian CPI isn't used in any other country in the world. (The UK used it in its Retail Prices Index, but its RPI no longer has National Statistic status.) The net acquisitions approach to OOH, which would give current housing price changes a lot bigger impact on the overall index, is already used in the target inflation indicators of the central banks of Australia and New Zealand, and Eurostat is working on adding such an OOH component in the inflation indicator for the European Central Bank. So far, the Bank of Canada hasn't done much to look at switching to a net acquisitions approach beyond spreading fake news about the Eurostat project to make it look like it is a much smaller deal than it actually is.  Canadians deserve a better central bank.

Taking a SWAG (Scientific Wild-Ass Guess) I'd say that what's pictured is a movie prop gun using either a Colt 1849 "Wells Fargo" or a Colt 1851 Navy cap and ball revolver as a starting point.  What's shown appears to actually be a cartridge conversion (to enable the firing of blanks?) as suggested by what appears to be a vestigial loading gate just behind the cylinder.  Curiously, the rebated cylinder (note how the diameter steps down toward the rear) would not be authentic to either an 1849 or 1851 Colt, which seems to reinforce the idea that this is a prop.  Google "Man With No Name Gun" to see a similar conversion that Clint Eastwood used in the 1960s spaghetti westerns.

Oh, and the cartridges?  From the fuzzy low-res image, they appear to be .32 ACP (Automatic Colt Pistol) rounds to my eye, as they seem to be too straight-walled to be 9x19 Luger rounds, and it's just possible to discern (or imagine?) a semi-rim on the rearmost cartridge.

As I recall from twenty or so years ago, well managed investment accounts were returning close to 10% on notes issued by FNMA and GNMA, on municipal bonds, and on other instruments.  I don't recall that anyone was credibly predicting an end to the long economic expansion after WW II, and a guaranteed 7.5% return seemed like a safe bet.  But GDP growth has slowed to a snail's pace over the last decade for a variety or reasons that economists and everyone else are arguing over.  How quickly we forget the past, so that now 1% GDP and near 0% return on investment ( and even negative returns on bonds! ) seem to be accepted as the new normal.  Perhaps in twenty years returns will again be generous, and those retirees stuck with accounts returning 2% will be screaming?  Who knows?

My point is that it's easy in hindsight to blame others for their lack of foresight, which would have required a working crystal ball.  But future contracts should promise only what the markets return.

Differentiating between Canada and the US on whether health care is a right for citizens is misleading. In each country, all citizens receive some health care. What differs is how we answer "how much health care are citizens entitled to at what cost?" In health care for those under age 65, as in many things, Canada values solidarity more and liberty less than the US. In typically American fashion, I care less about population-level outcomes than I do about individual access, cost, and incentives for responsible behavior. With the growth of retail medicine in the US, prices for routine care are becoming lower and increasing transparent. What US citizens would like is access to pharmaceuticals at foreign prices. Then we wouldn't be shouldering the cost of drug development for the rest of the world. If this sounds too much like free trade of the sacred cow of health care to the authors, would they prefer high US export taxes on US pharma products and intellectual property?
